  "text": "By combining this dataset with results from the same raccoon sample that had previously been generated for the MHC class II [CITATION_1] , we obtained strong evidence for an interaction between the variables MAADiv of MHC class I and MAADiv of MHC class II of candidate males on their probability of being chosen by any female as a mating partner ( p-value ¼ 5.1 Â 10 25 ). For both MHC-I and MHC-II, more amino acid diversity among alleles possessed by males led to increased chances of fathering offspring, but these chances were enhanced when diversity was simultaneously high in the loci of both MHC classes (figure 2).",
